Orchestrates leaf-then-rollup context generation on top of an abstract `Fs`/`Agent` pair, and exposes it as a CLI (`ctx-summarize`). Consumers get a single entry point — `runner::run`/`run_with_prompts` via `cli::dispatch` or the `main` binary — that takes a repo-relative target list (or a ctx-access task cache id) and produces `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files under `.context/`, gated by access control and a blast-radius approval check; nothing outside this crate needs to know the write order or the prompt format.

The layering is fixed and load-bearing: `main`/`cli` handle argv and I/O only, `runner` is pure orchestration, and `fs`/`agent`/`cache` are the only seams touching disk or a subprocess — new logic should slot into one of these, not blur the boundary. `cpath` defines the `.context` mirror-path convention (leaf `.ctx`, `rollup.ctx`, `intent.md`, ancestor dirs) that both `runner` and `cache`/`cli` rely on; changing that mapping means updating every caller, and it duplicates equivalent logic in `ctx-access` pending a shared `ctx-core` crate. `fs::scope_matcher` (gitignore-syntax, `.ctxignore` + built-in `target/`) is the single definition of "in scope," reused by both the per-target deny gate in `runner::summarize_leaf` (via `ctx_core::access::deny_reason`) and externally by ctx-scan's walker — the two must stay consistent. `error.rs` is the shared vocabulary of failure modes across all of the above; a new failure path elsewhere in the crate should add a variant here rather than repurpose one.

Runtime order matters and is centralized in `runner`: all leaves are summarized before any rollup, and rollups run strictly leaf-up (deepest directories first, repo root last, per `cpath::ancestor_dirs`/`affected_dirs`), because each rollup read reconstructs its input by re-reading files this same run may have just written — reordering silently corrupts rollups rather than erroring. `runner::scope_check`'s `MAX_TARGETS` guard is not called internally by `run`/`run_with_prompts`; `cli::dispatch` is the one caller that invokes it (bypassable via `--approve`). Prompt text (`summarizer-leaf.md`/`summarizer-rollup.md`) is always external, loaded at runtime by `runner::load_prompts` — no prompt strings live in source anywhere in this crate. `intent.md` is read-only input throughout; nothing in this crate ever writes it. `agent.rs`'s `SubprocessAgent` and `fs.rs`'s `StdFs`/`Fs` trait are the two swappable seams that `main.rs` wires together for real runs and that tests replace with fakes.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence check is possible.